        <hl1>Forms of Health Care</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Marvin J Schissel letter comments on July 13 letter on ways of easing financial burden of health expenditures on aging Americans (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A July 13 letter writer suggests ways to ''ease the financial burden of health expenditures that our graying Americans bear.'' He sensibly recommends generic drugs, which are already widely used.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A July 13 letter writer suggests ways to ''ease the financial burden of health expenditures that our graying Americans bear.'' He sensibly recommends generic drugs, which are already widely used.</p>
        <p>But he also, less sensibly, suggests that we might ''pursue alternative forms of medicine.'' This would indeed cut down costs. Not only is alternative medicine cheaper to begin with, but an elderly patient who abandons standard treatment for ''alternative'' medicine is also likely to expire soon, thus eliminating all further medical expense.</p>
        <p>MARVIN J. SCHISSEL  Roslyn Heights, N.Y., July 14, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a dentist and vice president of the New York chapter, National Council Against Health Fraud.</p>
      </block>
